vitation with formation of blastocoel","Compaction with tight junction formation","Primitive streak formation with gastrulation","Implantation with cytotrophoblast invasion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe formation of a fluid-filled cavity (blastocoel) within the morula is called \u003Cstrong\u003Eblastocyst cavitation\u003C/strong\u003E. This process creates the blastocyst, which consists of an outer trophoblast layer and inner cell mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther key developmental processes that are not correct at this stage include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimitive streak formation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during week three of development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompaction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs earlier at the 8-cell stage (day three)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHatching\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after blastocyst formation when the embryo breaks free of the zona pellucida\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImplantation\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after hatching when the blastocyst attaches to the endometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blastocyst cavitation occurs around day five post-fertilisation through sodium pump activity creating a fluid-filled cavity,","The inner cell mass forms embryonic tissues while the trophoblast forms placental tissues.","The blastocoel is the fluid-filled cavity within the blastocyst."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48277"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15840"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi